# Contributor Covenant Code of Conduct

## Our Pledge

We as members, contributors, and leaders pledge to make participation in our
community a harassment-free experience for everyone, regardless of age, body
size, visible or invisible disability, ethnicity, sex characteristics, gender
identity and expression, level of experience, education, socio-economic status,
nationality, personal appearance, race, religion, or sexual identity
and orientation.

We pledge to act and interact in ways that contribute to an open, welcoming,
diverse, inclusive, and healthy community.

## Our Standards

Examples of behavior that contributes to a positive environment for our
community include:

* Demonstrating empathy and kindness toward other people
* Being respectful of differing opinions, viewpoints, and experiences
* Giving and gracefully accepting constructive feedback
* Accepting responsibility and apologizing to those affected by our mistakes,
  and learning from the experience
* Focusing on what is best not just for us as individuals, but for the
  overall community

Examples of unacceptable behavior include:

* The use of sexualized language or imagery, and sexual attention or
  advances of any kind
* Trolling, insulting or derogatory comments, and personal or political attacks
* Public or private harassment
* Publishing others' private information, such as a physical or email
  address, without their explicit permission
* Other conduct which could reasonably be considered inappropriate in a
  professional setting

## Enforcement Responsibilities

Community leaders are responsible for clarifying and enforcing our standards of
acceptable behavior and will take appropriate and fair corrective action in
response to any behavior that they deem inappropriate, threatening, offensive,
or harmful.

Community leaders have the right and responsibility to remove, edit, or reject
comments, commits, code, wiki edits, issues, and other contributions that are
not aligned to this Code of Conduct, and will communicate reasons for moderation
decisions when appropriate.

## Scope

This Code of Conduct applies within all community spaces, and also applies when
an individual is officially representing the community in public spaces.
Examples of representing our community include using an official e-mail address,
posting via an official social media account, or acting as an appointed
representative at an online or offline event.

## Enforcement

Instances of abusive, harassing, or otherwise unacceptable behavior may be
reported to the community leaders responsible for enforcement at
mason@cosmos-simulation.example.com.
All complaints will be reviewed and investigated promptly and fairly.

All community leaders are obligated to respect the privacy and security of the
reporter of any incident.

## Enforcement Guidelines

Community leaders will follow these Community Impact Guidelines in determining
the consequences for any action they deem in violation of this Code of Conduct:

### 1. Correction

**Community Impact:** Use of inappropriate language or other behavior deemed
unprofessional or unwelcome in the community.

**Consequence:** A private, written warning from community leaders, providing
clarity around the nature of the violation and an explanation of why the
behavior was inappropriate. A public apology may be requested.

### 2. Warning

**Community Impact:** A violation through a single incident or series
of actions.

**Consequence:** A warning with consequences for continued behavior. No
interaction with the people involved, including unsolicited interaction with
those enforcing the Code of Conduct, for a specified period of time. This
includes avoiding interactions in community spaces as well as external channels
like social media. Violating these terms may lead to a temporary or
permanent ban.

### 3. Temporary Ban

**Community Impact:** A serious violation of community standards, including
sustained inappropriate behavior.

**Consequence:** A temporary ban from any sort of interaction or public
communication with the community for a specified period of time. No public
or private interaction with the people involved, including unsolicited interaction
with those enforcing the Code of Conduct, is allowed during this period.
Violating these terms may lead to a permanent ban.

### 4. Permanent Ban

**Community Impact:** Demonstrating a pattern of violation of community
standards, including sustained inappropriate behavior, harassment of an
individual, or aggression toward or disparagement of classes of individuals.

**Consequence:** A permanent ban from any sort of public interaction within
the community.

## Attribution

This Code of Conduct is adapted from the [Contributor Covenant][homepage],
version 2.0, available at
https://www.contributor-covenant.org/version/2/0/code_of_conduct.html.

Community Impact Guidelines were inspired by [Mozilla's code of conduct
enforcement ladder](https://github.com/mozilla/diversity).

[homepage]: https://www.contributor-covenant.org

For answers to common questions about this code of conduct, see the FAQ at
https://www.contributor-covenant.org/faq. Translations are available at
https://www.contributor-covenant.org/translations.

This Code of Conduct is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 4.0
International License. You are free to share and adapt this document for
your own projects, provided you give appropriate credit and indicate if
changes were made.

---

# Contributing

## How to Contribute

The Cosmos Simulation project welcomes contributions from anyone who shares
our passion for space exploration and education. Whether you're a seasoned
developer, a science enthusiast, or just getting started with open source,
there are many ways you can contribute to our project.

Contributions are not limited to code. We value and appreciate:
- Bug reports and issue submissions
- Documentation improvements
- Scientific accuracy reviews
- Translation work
- Visual design and UI/UX improvements
- Testing and quality assurance
- Community support and mentoring
- Feature suggestions and feedback

## Contribution Types

### Code Contributions
- **Bug Fixes**: Identify and resolve issues in the codebase
- **New Features**: Implement new functionality for the simulation
- **Performance Improvements**: Optimize existing code for better performance
- **Refactoring**: Improve code structure without changing functionality
- **Test Coverage**: Add or improve unit, integration, or E2E tests

### Documentation Contributions
- **Tutorial Writing**: Create guides for new users
- **API Documentation**: Improve code documentation and examples
- **Error Message Improvements**: Make error messages clearer and more helpful
- **Translation**: Translate documentation into other languages

### Scientific Contributions
- **Data Verification**: Check astronomical data against authoritative sources
- **Accuracy Improvements**: Suggest and implement more accurate calculations
- **New Celestial Bodies**: Propose and add data for new objects

### Community Contributions
- **Issue Triage**: Help organize and prioritize issues
- **Code Review**: Review pull requests and provide constructive feedback
- **Mentoring**: Help new contributors get started
- **Community Support**: Answer questions in discussions

## Getting Started

### For New Contributors
1. **Explore the Repository**: Familiarize yourself with the project structure
2. **Start Small**: Begin with beginner-friendly issues labeled "good first issue"
3. **Set Up Your Environment**: Follow the setup instructions in the README
4. **Join the Community**: Introduce yourself in our discussion forums
5. **Find a Task**: Look for issues that match your skills and interests

### For Experienced Contributors
1. **Review Pull Requests**: Help maintainers by reviewing others' contributions
2. **Mentor Newcomers**: Guide new contributors through their first contributions
3. **Propose Features**: Submit feature proposals for project direction input
4. **Participate in Design**: Join discussions on major architectural decisions
5. **Take Ownership**: Lead efforts on significant features or subsystems

## Pull Request Process

1. **Create a Branch**: Create a feature branch from main for your changes
2. **Make Changes**: Implement your changes with appropriate tests and docs
3. **Submit PR**: Open a pull request with a clear description of your changes
4. **Address Feedback**: Respond to reviewer comments and make improvements
5. **Merge**: Once approved, your contribution will be merged into the project

### Pull Request Guidelines
- Keep PRs focused on a single concern
- Write clear commit messages
- Include tests for new functionality
- Update documentation as needed
- Ensure CI passes before requesting review

## Contribution Recognition

We believe in acknowledging all contributions to our project:

- **Contributor List**: All contributors are listed in our CONTRIBUTORS file
- **Release Notes**: Significant contributions are highlighted in release announcements
- **Special Recognition**: Outstanding contributors may be nominated for special acknowledgment
- **Role Progression**: Active contributors may be invited to become maintainers

All contributions matter, regardless of size. Every bug fix, documentation improvement,
and helpful comment makes our project better.

---

# Collaboration

## Team Collaboration Guidelines

Effective collaboration is essential to the success of the Cosmos Simulation project.
We believe that the best solutions emerge when diverse perspectives work together.

### Core Collaboration Principles
- **Respect**: Treat all collaborators with respect, regardless of experience level
- **Transparency**: Be open about your work, decisions, and challenges
- **Constructiveness**: Offer feedback that helps improve the project
- **Inclusivity**: Welcome diverse viewpoints and backgrounds
- **Patience**: Remember that everyone is learning and may need guidance

### Working Together Effectively
- Communicate clearly and concisely
- Share context and background information
- Ask clarifying questions when needed
- Celebrate shared successes
- Learn from mistakes without blame

## Code Review Practices

Code review is a collaborative process that improves code quality and builds community.

### For Reviewers
- Review promptly and thoroughly
- Provide specific, actionable feedback
- Distinguish between suggestions and requirements
- Acknowledge good work alongside improvements
- Be respectful and constructive

### For Authors
- Write clear, self-documenting code
- Respond to feedback with an open mind
- Ask questions when feedback is unclear
- Explain your reasoning when needed
- Thank reviewers for their input

### Review Focus Areas
- **Correctness**: Does the code do what it's supposed to?
- **Maintainability**: Is the code easy to understand and modify?
- **Performance**: Are there performance considerations?
- **Testing**: Are there adequate tests?
- **Documentation**: Is the code properly documented?

## Communication Channels

### Primary Channels
- **GitHub Issues**: For bug reports, feature requests, and discussions
- **Pull Requests**: For code changes and reviews
- **Discussions**: For general questions and community conversations
- **Email**: For private inquiries and sensitive matters

### Communication Best Practices
- Use the appropriate channel for your message
- Search before posting to avoid duplicates
- Be specific and provide context
- Stay on topic in discussions
- Follow up on your conversations

### Response Expectations
- Issues: Initial response within 48 hours
- Pull Requests: Review feedback within 5 business days
- General inquiries: Response within 72 hours

## Working Together Effectively

### Async-First Communication
- Write clear, detailed messages
- Include all relevant context
- Be patient with time zone differences
- Use documentation to share knowledge

### Synchronous Communication
- Respect others' time and schedules
- Come prepared to meetings
- Share outcomes with those who couldn't attend
- Balance speaking and listening

### Handling Disagreements
- Focus on the issue, not the person
- Seek to understand different perspectives
- Look for common ground
- Escalate constructively when needed
- Accept that not all disagreements will be resolved

---

# Roles

## Contributor Levels

### Casual Contributors
**Definition**: Contributors who make occasional contributions to the project.

**Characteristics**:
- Submit occasional bug fixes or small improvements
- May participate in discussions occasionally
- Typically have 1-10 contributions

**Expectations**:
- Follow the Code of Conduct
- Submit quality contributions
- Respond to feedback on their contributions

### Regular Contributors
**Definition**: Contributors who demonstrate consistent engagement with the project.

**Characteristics**:
- Regular contributions over an extended period
- Active participation in discussions
- Typically have 10-50 contributions
- Show understanding of project direction

**Expectations** (in addition to Casual expectations):
- Help review others' pull requests
- Answer questions from new contributors
- Participate in community discussions
- Show commitment to project success

### Major Contributors
**Definition**: Contributors who have made significant, sustained contributions.

**Characteristics**:
- Multiple substantial contributions (features, subsystems)
- Demonstrated leadership in specific areas
- Typically have 50+ contributions
- Recognized by maintainers and community

**Expectations** (in addition to Regular expectations):
- Lead significant features or initiatives
- Mentor new and casual contributors
- Participate in project planning
- Represent the project positively

## Maintainers

Maintainers are contributors who have demonstrated exceptional commitment
and have been granted additional privileges and responsibilities.

### Maintainer Responsibilities
- Review and merge pull requests
- Triage and respond to issues
- Enforce the Code of Conduct
- Guide project technical direction
- Mentor and support contributors
- Manage releases and deployments
- Communicate project decisions

### Maintainer Privileges
- Write access to the repository
- Ability to merge pull requests
- Access to project management tools
- Voting rights on major decisions

### Becoming a Maintainer
Major contributors may be invited to become maintainers based on:
- Consistent, high-quality contributions
- Demonstrated understanding of the codebase
- Active participation in code review
- Positive community interactions
- Willingness to take on maintenance responsibilities

## Project Leads

Project leads have overall responsibility for the project's direction and health.

### Project Lead Responsibilities
- Set strategic direction for the project
- Make final decisions when consensus cannot be reached
- Ensure project remains true to mission and values
- Foster a healthy, inclusive community
- Mediate disputes and resolve conflicts
- Represent the project externally
- Manage project resources and priorities

### Project Lead Selection
Project leads are selected from maintainers based on:
- Demonstrated leadership and vision
- Strong technical understanding
- Community trust and respect
- Commitment to project success
- Ability to work with diverse stakeholders

## Role Promotion Criteria

### From Casual to Regular
- Demonstrated consistent contribution over time
- Quality contributions that meet project standards
- Positive community interactions
- Understanding of project processes

### From Regular to Major
- Significant contributions to major features
- Leadership on project initiatives
- Active mentorship of other contributors
- Recognition from maintainers and community

### From Major to Maintainer
- Sustained major contributor status
- Proven ability to review contributions
- Demonstrated understanding of project vision
- Willingness to take on maintenance responsibilities
- Nomination by existing maintainers

### Maintaining Roles
All roles require ongoing participation:
- Inactive contributors may have roles reduced
- Maintainers must actively review and respond
- Project leads must maintain community engagement

### Role Transitions
- Role changes are announced to the community
- Contributors may step down from roles voluntarily
- Roles may be revoked for Code of Conduct violations
- Appeals may be submitted for role decisions

---

# Cosmos Simulation Project Extended Community Guidelines

## Introduction

Welcome to the Cosmos Simulation project! This document provides comprehensive
guidelines for community participation, collaboration, and communication. As an
open-source initiative aimed at creating an accurate and educational solar system
simulation, we value the contributions of all community members and strive to
maintain a welcoming, productive, and innovative environment.

This extended guidelines document supplements the Contributor Covenant Code of
Conduct with specific provisions tailored to our project's unique characteristics,
including its educational mission, scientific accuracy requirements, and the
diverse backgrounds of our contributors.

## Project Mission and Values

### Our Mission

The Cosmos Simulation project aims to create a scientifically accurate, visually
compelling, and educationally valuable simulation of our solar system. We believe
that understanding our cosmic neighborhood is fundamental to appreciating our
place in the universe and advancing scientific literacy worldwide.

### Core Values

Our community is built upon several core values that guide all our interactions
and decisions:

**Scientific Integrity:** We are committed to maintaining the highest standards
of scientific accuracy in all aspects of our simulation. This means we welcome
scrutiny of our data, calculations, and rendering techniques, and we embrace
opportunities to improve our accuracy based on new research and observations.

**Educational Excellence:** As an educational tool, we recognize our responsibility
to present information clearly, accurately, and accessibly. We strive to make
complex astronomical concepts understandable for users of all backgrounds and
ages.

**Open Collaboration:** We believe that the best solutions emerge from diverse
perspectives working together. We encourage contributions from people with
different skills, experiences, and viewpoints.

**Respect for Diversity:** Our community includes contributors from around the
world with varied cultural backgrounds, native languages, and areas of expertise.
We celebrate this diversity and strive to create an inclusive environment where
everyone can contribute meaningfully.

**Transparency:** We maintain open communication about our decisions, priorities,
and challenges. We share our roadmap, discuss design choices, and welcome input
from the community.

## Getting Started with Contributing

### For New Contributors

If you're new to the Cosmos Simulation project, we warmly welcome you! Here are
some steps to help you get started:

1. **Explore the Project:** Begin by exploring our repository to understand the
   project structure, current features, and ongoing development efforts. The README
   file provides an overview, and our documentation folder contains detailed
   information about various components.

2. **Set Up Your Environment:** Follow our setup instructions to get the development
   environment running on your machine. Our documentation includes step-by-step
   guides for different operating systems and development setups.

3. **Start Small:** We recommend beginning with small, well-defined tasks such as
   fixing typos in documentation, improving comments, or addressing minor bugs.
   This helps you learn the codebase and build relationships with other contributors.

4. **Ask Questions:** Don't hesitate to ask questions! Our community is here to help.
   Use our discussion forums, chat channels, or issue comments to seek clarification
   or guidance.

### For Experienced Contributors

Experienced contributors play a crucial role in mentoring newcomers, reviewing
contributions, and advancing the project's technical goals. We encourage you to:

- Review pull requests from other contributors and provide constructive feedback
- Mentor new contributors and help them learn the codebase
- Propose new features through our feature request process
- Participate in design discussions to help shape the project's future direction

## Communication Guidelines

### General Communication Principles

Effective communication is essential for successful collaboration. All community
members should adhere to the following principles:

- **Be Clear and Concise:** Express your ideas clearly and concisely. When
  discussing technical matters, provide enough context for others to understand
  your point without overwhelming them with unnecessary details.
- **Be Respectful:** Treat all community members with respect, regardless of their
  experience level, background, or perspective. Disagreements are natural, but
  they should be handled professionally and constructively.
- **Be Patient:** Remember that many community members communicate in a language
  that may not be their first. Be patient with communication style differences
  and clarify when needed.
- **Be Accountable:** Take responsibility for your words and actions. If you make
  a mistake, acknowledge it and work to correct it.

### Issue Tracking Guidelines

When creating or responding to issues, please follow these guidelines:

- Search before creating to see if a similar issue already exists
- Provide detailed information when reporting bugs, including steps to reproduce
- Use appropriate labels to help categorize issues
- Keep discussions focused on the specific issue at hand
- Follow up on issues you're working on and communicate about delays

### Pull Request Guidelines

Pull requests are the primary mechanism for contributing code to the project:

- Create focused pull requests that address a single, well-defined concern
- Write clear descriptions of what your pull request does and why
- Keep pull requests updated based on feedback
- Respond to feedback promptly and constructively
- Be patient with the review process

## Technical Standards

### Code Style and Conventions

Consistent code style makes the codebase more readable and maintainable:

- Follow modern JavaScript conventions (ES6+ features where appropriate)
- Use meaningful variable and function names
- Include comprehensive comments for complex logic
- Document all public functions, classes, and modules with JSDoc

### Scientific Accuracy

As a scientific simulation, accuracy is paramount:

- Verify astronomical data against authoritative sources (NASA, JPL, etc.)
- Document uncertainties in data sources clearly
- Test rendering accuracy for relative sizes, positions, and movements
- Update data and models as scientific understanding evolves

### Performance Considerations

A smooth simulation requires attention to performance:

- Be mindful of CPU, memory, and GPU usage
- Consider performance implications when designing new features
- Handle edge cases gracefully without causing performance spikes
- Document performance characteristics of new features

## Community Roles and Responsibilities

### Contributors

All community members who contribute to the project are considered contributors.
Contributors are expected to:

- Follow the Code of Conduct in all community interactions
- Submit high-quality contributions that meet project standards
- Respond promptly to feedback on their contributions
- Help other contributors when possible
- Communicate respectfully and constructively

### Maintainers

Maintainers are contributors who have demonstrated consistent commitment to
the project and have been granted additional privileges:

- Review and respond to pull requests in a timely manner
- Triage and respond to issues appropriately
- Enforce the Code of Conduct consistently
- Make decisions about project direction with community input
- Mentor and support new contributors

### Project Leads

Project leads have overall responsibility for the project's direction and health:

- Set the strategic direction for the project
- Make final decisions when consensus cannot be reached
- Ensure the project remains true to its mission and values
- Foster a healthy, inclusive community
- Mediate disputes when necessary

## Conflict Resolution

Disagreements are natural in any collaborative project. When conflicts arise,
we encourage the following approach:

1. **Direct Communication:** Try to resolve issues through direct, respectful
   communication. Often, misunderstandings can be cleared up through simple
   clarification.

2. **Seek Mediation:** If direct communication doesn't resolve the issue, seek
   mediation from other community members or maintainers.

3. **Formal Resolution:** If the issue cannot be resolved through informal means,
   it may be escalated for formal resolution by project leads.

4. **Appeals:** Decisions can be appealed to the project leads for a final determination.

## Acknowledging Contributions

We value all contributions to the project and recognize contributors in several
ways:

- All contributors are acknowledged in our CONTRIBUTORS file
- Significant contributions are highlighted in release notes and announcements
- Code and documentation retain appropriate attribution per open source licenses
- Outstanding contributors may be nominated for special recognition

## Contact Information

For questions about this Code of Conduct or community guidelines, please contact:

- **General Inquiries:** info@cosmos-simulation.example.com
- **Code of Conduct Reports:** conduct@cosmos-simulation.example.com
- **Technical Support:** support@cosmos-simulation.example.com
- **Security Concerns:** security@cosmos-simulation.example.com

---

## Comprehensive Behavioral Guidelines

### What You SHOULD Do

The following behaviors are encouraged and expected from all community members:

**Communication Best Practices:**
- Greet new members and help them feel welcome
- Use clear, respectful language that all contributors can understand
- Provide constructive feedback that helps others improve
- Acknowledge questions even if you cannot answer them fully
- Explain technical concepts patiently when helping newer contributors
- Verify information before sharing it as fact, especially scientific data
- Cite sources when providing astronomical or scientific information
- Ask clarifying questions when you don't understand something
- Use inclusive language that welcomes contributors of all backgrounds

**Collaboration Best Practices:**
- Review others' pull requests with helpful, specific comments
- Test contributions before approving them in code review
- Document your code thoroughly so others can understand it
- Write tests for new features to ensure long-term reliability
- Update documentation when you make changes to the codebase
- Respond to review comments within a reasonable timeframe
- Break large changes into smaller, manageable pull requests
- Communicate delays or issues with assigned tasks promptly
- Seek help when you're stuck rather than remaining blocked

**Community Participation Best Practices:**
- Participate in community discussions and share your expertise
- Mentor new contributors and help them learn the codebase
- Report bugs with detailed steps to reproduce the issue
- Suggest improvements based on your experience using the project
- Respect the time and effort others have invested in their work
- Celebrate the successes of other community members
- Remain patient with contributors who are still learning
- Acknowledge your mistakes and work to correct them
- Follow through on commitments you make to the community

**Technical Best Practices:**
- Follow the project's coding standards and style guidelines
- Run tests and linting tools before submitting contributions
- Use meaningful variable and function names that describe their purpose
- Keep contributions focused on the specific task at hand
- Update dependencies when security vulnerabilities are discovered
- Consider performance implications of your changes
- Backup your work and use version control for all significant changes
- Verify that your changes work correctly before submitting them
- Respect the project's branching strategy and workflow

**Respect and Inclusion Best Practices:**
- Treat all contributors with equal respect regardless of experience level
- Recognize that people have different communication styles and backgrounds
- Give others the benefit of the doubt when interpreting their words
- Create space for quieter voices to be heard in discussions
- Represent the project positively in all public interactions
- Respect diverse perspectives and approaches to solving problems
- Use people's preferred names and pronouns
- Accommodate different time zones and work schedules when collaborating
- Be understanding of life circumstances that may affect availability
- Promote an environment where everyone feels safe to contribute

### What You SHOULD NOT Do

The following behaviors are prohibited and will result in consequences:

**Communication Violations:**
- Use inflammatory, offensive, or discriminatory language
- Make personal attacks or insults against other contributors
- Dismiss or belittle others' questions or contributions
- Use sarcasm or irony in ways that could be misunderstood as hostility
- Respond to questions with contempt or impatience
- Share private information about contributors without consent
- Create multiple accounts to manipulate voting or evade bans
- Flood channels with repetitive or off-topic messages
- Use the project's communication channels for unrelated commercial activities
- Impersonate project maintainers or official representatives

**Collaboration Violations:**
- Submit low-quality contributions without testing or documentation
- Abandon pull requests without explanation or hand-off
- Ignore review feedback and refuse to make improvements
- Submit very large pull requests that cannot be effectively reviewed
- Make changes that break existing functionality without good reason
- Include malicious code, backdoors, or security vulnerabilities
- Commit sensitive information like API keys or passwords
- Revert others' changes without proper discussion and rationale
- Bypass code review by committing directly to protected branches
- Claim ownership of code that you did not write or create

**Technical Violations:**
- Introduce known security vulnerabilities into the codebase
- Use outdated or deprecated dependencies without justification
- Ignore performance issues that significantly impact users
- Circumvent testing requirements or submit untested code
- Introduce code that is difficult to understand or maintain
- Make changes that violate the project's license agreements
- Include copyrighted material without proper licensing
- Submit code that does not compile or run on supported platforms
- Use the project to distribute malware or harmful software
- Interfere with the project's continuous integration systems

**Community Violations:**
- Harass, threaten, or intimidate other community members
- Engage in discriminatory behavior based on protected characteristics
- Engage in any form of sexual harassment or inappropriate advances
- Retaliate against others for reporting code of conduct violations
- Create a hostile environment that drives contributors away
- Spread misinformation about the project or its contributors
- Manipulate or falsify contribution statistics or metrics
- Exploit the project for personal gain without authorization
- Disrupt community events or meetings with disruptive behavior
- Encourage others to violate this code of conduct

**Respect and Inclusion Violations:**
- Use slurs, hate speech, or symbols associated with hatred
- Mock or ridicule others' accents, language skills, or backgrounds
- Assume someone's identity, experience level, or expertise
- Gatekeep or make newcomers feel unwelcome in any way
- Dismiss contributions based on the contributor's identity
- Create or share content that is pornographic, violent, or disturbing
- Discuss controversial political or religious topics in project spaces
- Minimize or deny the experiences of marginalized contributors
- Exclude others from participation based on geographic location
- Make assumptions about someone's abilities or circumstances

---

## Severity Levels and Consequences

The Cosmos Simulation project maintains a comprehensive enforcement system
with distinct severity levels:

### Level 1: Minor Verbal Correction
**Examples:** Slightly informal language, minor formatting errors  
**Consequence:** Private, informal reminder. No formal record.

### Level 2: Formal Written Warning
**Examples:** Repeated minor violations, dismissive language  
**Consequence:** Formal written warning kept in project records.

### Level 3: Temporary Discussion Ban
**Examples:** Continued violations, unproductive comments, off-topic discussions  
**Consequence:** 3-day ban from discussion channels.

### Level 4: Pull Request Moratorium
**Examples:** Multiple low-quality pull requests, ignoring feedback  
**Consequence:** 7-day prohibition from submitting new pull requests.

### Level 5: Restricted Participation
**Examples:** Dismissive comments, inconsistent communication guidelines  
**Consequence:** 14-day restricted participation with sponsor requirement.

### Level 6: Temporary Community Ban
**Examples:** Insulting language, public embarrassment, personal attacks  
**Consequence:** 30-day complete suspension from all project spaces.

### Level 7: Extended Community Ban
**Examples:** Harassment, discriminatory remarks, sustained negativity  
**Consequence:** 90-day ban with formal review before reinstatement.

### Level 8: Permanent Account Suspension
**Examples:** Sustained harassment, threats, malicious code, identity fraud  
**Consequence:** Permanent ban from all project access.

### Level 9: Legal Referral
**Examples:** Copyright infringement, defamation, fraud, unauthorized trademark use  
**Consequence:** Permanent ban with referral to legal authorities.

### Level 10: Emergency Project Protection
**Examples:** Security breaches, infrastructure attacks, malware introduction  
**Consequence:** Immediate access revocation, law enforcement coordination.

---

## Escalation and Deescalation Guidelines

### Escalation Path

1. **Initial Detection:** Any community member may identify and report violations
2. **Initial Assessment:** Coordinator reviews report to determine severity
3. **Investigation:** Evidence gathering for severity levels 3 and above
4. **Determination:** Decision about violation and consequence
5. **Notification:** Individual notified with explanation and evidence
6. **Appeal Process:** Available for severity levels 5 and above

### Deescalation Considerations

In appropriate cases, deescalation may be warranted:
- First-time violations of low severity
- Violations stemming from misunderstanding
- Personal circumstances affecting behavior
- Demonstrated remorse and commitment to change
- Genuine efforts at repair and reconciliation

Deescalation does not apply to severe violations or repeat offenders.

### Appeal Process

For violations of severity level 5 and above:
1. Submit formal written appeal within 14 days
2. Appeal review committee is assembled
3. Committee reviews all evidence and renders decision
4. Decision is final for severity levels 5-7
5. External review available for severity levels 8-10 at discretion

---

## Reporting Violations

All violations should be reported to ensure community safety:

- **Report Email:** conduct@cosmos-simulation.example.com
- **Emergency Reports:** security@cosmos-simulation.example.com

**Reporting Principles:**
- Reports should be made in good faith
- Retaliation against reporters is itself a violation
- All reports are treated confidentially
- Reports are reviewed by trained coordinators
- False reports may result in consequences for the reporter

---

## Enforcement Team

The Code of Conduct is enforced by trained coordinators:

- **Level 1-2:** Community members and any maintainer
- **Level 3-4:** Senior maintainers and coordinators
- **Level 5-7:** Project leads with review committee
- **Level 8-10:** Project leads with external consultation

All enforcement decisions are documented and tracked for consistency.

---

## Glossary

**Key Terms:**
- **Branch:** A parallel version of the repository for independent development
- **Bug:** An error or flaw producing unexpected results
- **Code Review:** Examining code changes before they are merged
- **Commit:** A saved change with a unique identifier
- **Contributor:** Anyone who submits work to the project
- **Documentation:** Written materials explaining the project
- **Issue:** A tracking item for bugs, features, or tasks
- **Maintainer:** Contributor with project management responsibilities
- **Pull Request:** A proposal to submit changes
- **Repository:** Storage location for project files and history

**Project-Specific Terms:**
- **API:** Rules allowing different software components to communicate
- **Astronomical Unit (AU):** Approximately 150 million kilometers
- **J2000:** Julian date epoch starting January 1, 2000
- **Kepler's Laws:** Three scientific laws describing planetary motion
- **Three.js:** JavaScript 3D library used for rendering
- **WebGL:** JavaScript API for rendering 2D/3D graphics in browsers

---

