## Closing Thoughts

The Cosmos Simulation project exists because of the collective effort of
people who share a passion for space exploration and education. By working
together respectfully and collaboratively, we can create something truly
remarkable that inspires future generations to look up at the stars and
wonder about the universe we inhabit.

We thank every member of our community for their contributions, whether
they're writing code, filing issues, providing feedback, or simply using
the simulation and sharing it with others. Every interaction helps make
this project better.

Together, we're building a window to the cosmos. Let's keep it open,
welcoming, and full of wonder.

## Development Workflow

### Overview

The Cosmos Simulation project follows a structured development workflow that
ensures code quality, proper review, and smooth collaboration among contributors.
Understanding and following this workflow is essential for anyone who wishes
to contribute meaningfully to the project.

### Development Cycle

Our development follows a continuous integration approach with regular release
cycles. Development occurs on feature branches that are merged into the main
branch after thorough review and testing. We maintain a stable main branch that
always contains production ready code, while development work happens on
dedicated branches.

Feature development follows a predictable pattern: first, the feature or fix
is discussed and agreed upon in issues or design documents. Then, a branch is
created from main, development work is completed with appropriate testing,
and finally, the branch is submitted for review and merging.

### Development Environment Setup

Setting up a proper development environment is crucial for effective
contribution. Contributors should ensure they have the following configured:
Node.js and npm for JavaScript development, Git for version control, a modern
code editor with appropriate extensions, and any project specific tools
detailed in our documentation.

We recommend configuring line ending handling for cross platform compatibility,
setting up pre commit hooks for code quality checks, and our build and
test scripts before making significant contributions.

### Continuous Integration

All contributions go through our continuous integration pipeline, which
includes automated testing, linting, and build processes. Contributions that
fail CI checks will not be merged until all issues are resolved.

The CI pipeline runs the full test suite, performs static code analysis,
checks code formatting compliance, builds the project for all supported
platforms, and validates documentation changes. Contributors should run these
checks locally before submitting their work to avoid unnecessary CI failures.

## Documentation Standards

### Purpose and Scope

Documentation is a critical part of the Cosmos Simulation project. Good
documentation helps users understand the simulation, assists developers in
understanding the codebase, and ensures the long term sustainability of the
project. All contributors are expected to contribute to documentation as
part of their contributions.

### Types of Documentation

The project maintains several categories of documentation: user facing
documentation that explains how to use the simulation, API documentation
that describes code interfaces and behavior, developer documentation that
guides new contributors through setup and contribution processes, and design
documentation that explains architectural decisions and trade offs.

Each type of documentation serves a distinct audience and purpose. When
contributing documentation, consider who your primary audience is and what
they need to understand.

### Documentation Style

All documentation should be clear, concise, and technically accurate. Use
consistent formatting throughout, including heading hierarchy, code formatting,
and terminology. Write in complete sentences with proper grammar, and avoid
unnecessary jargon unless it serves a specific technical purpose.

Code examples in documentation should be working and tested. If documenting
an API, include realistic usage examples that demonstrate common patterns.
When documenting complex concepts, start with a high level overview before
diving into details.

### Keeping Documentation Current

Outdated documentation is often worse than no documentation, as it can mislead
users and developers. When making changes that affect functionality, update
or note the documentation implications in your pull request. Flag known
documentation issues in issues so they can be addressed systematically.

## Testing Requirements

### Why Testing Matters

As a scientific simulation, the Cosmos Simulation project has a responsibility
to produce accurate and reliable results. Testing is not optionalit is a
fundamental requirement for all contributions. Thorough testing helps catch
bugs early, prevents regression when changes are made, and provides confidence
that the simulation behaves as expected.

### Test Types

The project employs several levels of testing to ensure quality. Unit tests
verify that individual functions and components work correctly in isolation.
Integration tests verify that multiple components work together correctly.
End to end tests verify that the complete simulation behaves correctly from
a user's perspective. Performance tests ensure that the simulation maintains
acceptable performance characteristics.

Each type of test serves a different purpose and catches different classes
of problems. Contributions should include appropriate tests at multiple levels
whenever possible.

### Test Coverage

While we do not mandate specific coverage percentages, contributors should
strive for comprehensive test coverage of their changes. Critical functionality
should have near complete coverage. Bug fixes should include tests that verify
the fix and prevent regression. New features should include tests for all
public interfaces and important internal logic.

### Writing Good Tests

Good tests are reliable, readable, and maintainable. They should fail only
when actual problems exist, not due to timing issues, environment differences,
or test interdependencies. Tests should be easy to understand, with clear
names and structure. They should be maintainable, with shared setup and
teardown handled appropriately.

Avoid testing implementation details when possible; instead, test observable
behavior. This makes tests more resilient to refactoring and more useful as
regression detectors.

## Security Guidelines

### Security First Approach

Security is a fundamental concern for any software project. The Cosmos
Simulation project, while primarily an educational and scientific tool,
still must handle security considerations thoughtfully. All contributors
should adopt a security first mindset when developing and reviewing code.

### Handling Sensitive Data

The project should never expose sensitive data such as API keys, passwords,
personal information, or internal system details. If contributions require
handling sensitive data, they must include appropriate protection mechanisms
and documentation of security considerations.

When in doubt about whether something should be included in the repository,
consult with maintainers before proceeding. It is easier to prevent a security
issue than to remediate one after it has been introduced.

### Dependency Security

Regularly review and update dependencies to address known vulnerabilities.
Use tools like npm audit or equivalent dependency scanning tools to identify
vulnerable packages. When vulnerabilities are found in dependencies, prioritize
updating to secure versions.

Avoid introducing new dependencies when existing ones meet the need, as each
dependency is a potential security liability. When new dependencies are
necessary, review their maintenance status, security history, and community
adoption before adoption.

### Reporting Security Issues

If you discover a security vulnerability in the project, do not report it in
public forums or issue trackers. Instead, contact the project leads directly
at security@cosmos simulation.example.com. This allows the team to assess and
address the vulnerability before it can be exploited.

## Accessibility Standards

### Commitment to Accessibility

The Cosmos Simulation project is committed to being accessible to all users,
including those with disabilities. We believe that scientific exploration
should be available to everyone, regardless of physical abilities.

### Visual Accessibility

The simulation should be usable by people with various visual abilities.
This includes providing sufficient color contrast, avoiding reliance on color
alone to convey information, supporting screen readers where applicable, and
allowing customization of visual elements such as size and contrast.

When adding visual features, consider how users with color blindness,
low vision, or other visual impairments will experience them. Provide text
alternatives for visual information where possible.

### Interaction Accessibility

Users should be able to interact with the simulation using various input
methods. This includes keyboard navigation for all major features, support
for assistive technologies, and consideration of users with motor impairments
who may have difficulty with precise inputs or rapid reactions.

### Documentation Accessibility

All documentation should be accessible to screen readers and other assistive
technologies. Use proper heading structure, provide alt text for images, and
ensure that code examples are accessible to users with visual impairments.

## Internationalization

### Supporting Multiple Languages

The Cosmos Simulation project aims to be accessible to a global audience.
This includes supporting multiple languages in the user interface, documentation,
and any user facing text. Internationalization (i18n) considerations should
be part of all contributions that affect users.

### String Management

All user facing strings should be externalized and marked for translation.
Avoid embedding strings directly in code. Use the project's internationalization
framework consistently, and follow established patterns for pluralization,
gender, and other linguistic considerations.

When adding new user facing strings, provide them in English as the project's
primary language, with clear context for translators. Avoid idioms, slang,
or culturally specific references that may not translate well.

### Localization Process

The project maintains translation files for supported languages. Contributors
can propose new translations or improvements to existing ones. Translations
should be reviewed by speakers of the target language for accuracy and
naturalness.

### Cultural Considerations

Be aware that users from different cultures may have different expectations
and conventions. Date and time formats, number formatting, and other
locale specific elements should adapt to user preferences. Avoid assumptions
about user location or preferences based on language alone.

## Release Management

### Release Philosophy

The Cosmos Simulation project follows a predictable release schedule to
provide users with regular updates and to manage the project's evolution
effectively. Releases include new features, bug fixes, and improvements
to existing functionality.

### Release Types

We distinguish between major releases, minor releases, and patch releases.
Major releases may include breaking changes and significant new features.
Minor releases add new features in a backward compatible manner. Patch
releases contain bug fixes and security updates only.

### Release Process

Releases follow a defined process that includes feature freeze periods,
testing phases, documentation updates, and announcement preparation. The
process ensures that releases are well tested and that users are properly
informed about changes.

Contributors should be aware of upcoming release schedules when planning
their contributions, particularly for changes that should be included in
specific releases.

### Version Numbering

The project follows semantic versioning (SemVer) for release numbering. This
communicates the nature of changes in each release and helps users understand
the compatibility implications of updating.

## Branching Strategy

### Main Branch

The main branch always contains production ready code. It is protected and
can only be updated through approved pull requests. Direct commits to main
are not allowed except by project maintainers in exceptional circumstances.

### Feature Branches

Feature branches are created for all substantive changes. Branch names should
be descriptive and follow a consistent format. For example, feature branches
might be named "feature/short description" or "fix/issue description".

### Release Branches

Release branches are created when preparing a new release. They allow for
final testing and bug fixes without disrupting ongoing development on main.
Release branches are named with the release version they will produce.

### Branch Lifecycle

Branches should be short lived and merged promptly after review. Long lived
branches create merge conflicts and complicate development. If a branch
cannot be merged quickly, communicate the reason and expected timeline to
the team.

## Commit Message Conventions

### Why Commit Messages Matter

Good commit messages are essential for understanding the history of the
project, troubleshooting issues, and collaborating effectively. Well written
commits make it easier to review changes, find when bugs were introduced,
and understand the rationale behind decisions.

### Commit Message Format

Each commit message should consist of a subject line and an optional body.
The subject line should be a short summary (50 characters or less) of the
change, written in the imperative mood. The body, when present, should
explain what changed and why, separated by a blank line from the subject.

### Subject Line Guidelines

Use the imperative mood ("Add feature" not "Added feature"). Capitalize the
first letter. Do not end with a period. Focus on what the commit does, not
why it was madethat context belongs in the body if needed.

### Commit Size

Each commit should represent a single logical change. Related changes can
be grouped in a single commit if they are small and truly inseparable.
Avoid making large commits that mix multiple concerns, as this makes review
and rollback more difficult.

### Atomic Commits

Prefer atomic commits that do one thing well. This makes it easier to
understand changes, find bugs, and selectively apply or revert commits.
If a change affects multiple files to implement a single feature, those
changes can reasonably be in one commit.

## Issue Labeling System

### Purpose of Labels

Labels help organize and prioritize issues in the repository. Consistent
label usage makes it easier to find relevant issues, track project progress,
and understand the state of the codebase.

### Label Categories

The project uses several categories of labels: type labels indicate the
kind of issue (bug, feature, documentation, etc.), status labels indicate
where the issue stands (confirmed, in progress, blocked, etc.), priority
labels indicate importance and urgency, and area labels indicate which
part of the project the issue affects.

### Label Definitions

Contributors should understand the meaning of each label and apply them
appropriately. When creating or editing issues, add relevant labels to
help with organization. When working on issues, update their status labels
as progress is made.

### Label Consistency

Use existing labels rather than creating new ones. If you believe a new
label is necessary, discuss it with maintainers before creating it.
Too many labels can be as problematic as too few, as they reduce clarity
and consistency.

## Code of Conduct for Events

### Event Participation

The Cosmos Simulation project may participate in or host events such as
conferences, meetups, workshops, or virtual gatherings. All participants
in project events are expected to follow this Code of Conduct, just as
they would in online community spaces.

### Event Specific Guidelines

In addition to the general Code of Conduct, event participants should
respect venue rules and policies, be mindful of noise levels and shared
spaces, represent the project positively to external audiences, and
follow any event specific guidelines communicated by organizers.

### Virtual Events

Virtual events have their own considerations. Participants should use
their real names or clearly identified pseudonyms, minimize background
noise and distractions, be patient with technology issues, and respect
the time and attention of other participants.

### Event Representation

Individuals representing the project at external events have additional
responsibilities. They should accurately represent the project's positions
and capabilities, clarify when speaking personally versus representing
the project, and defer to official project communications when appropriate.

## Social Media Guidelines

### Official Social Media Presence

The project maintains official presences on social media platforms.
These accounts are managed by designated project members and follow
these social media guidelines.

### Account Representation

Official accounts should use official project branding and profile
information. Posts should represent the project's official positions
and communications. When sharing third party content, credit the
original source and ensure it aligns with project values.

### Engaging with the Community

Project social media accounts should engage constructively with the
community. This includes responding to questions when appropriate,
acknowledging contributions and achievements, and sharing relevant
updates and announcements.

### Personal Social Media

When project contributors discuss the project on personal social media,
they should clarify that they are speaking personally and not officially
representing the project. This prevents confusion about official project
positions and protects both the individual and the project.

## Third Party Services

### Service Integration

The Cosmos Simulation project may integrate with third party services
for various purposes such as continuous integration, documentation hosting,
or data services. All such integrations should follow these guidelines.

### Service Selection

Before adding a new third party service integration, consider whether
the service is necessary and whether there are alternatives. Evaluate
the service's privacy policy, data handling practices, reliability,
and long term viability. Consider the maintenance burden of the
integration.

### Service Configuration

Service configurations should be documented and should use appropriate
authentication and authorization mechanisms. Sensitive credentials should
never be committed to the repository. Services should be configured to
minimize data exposure and respect user privacy.

### Service Deprecation

When third party services are discontinued or significantly changed,
integrations should be updated or removed. Plan for service transitions
and communicate changes to users in advance when possible.

## Dependency Management

### Dependency Philosophy

Dependencies extend the project's capabilities but also introduce risks
and maintenance burden. Each dependency should be carefully considered
and justified. Prefer minimal dependencies and favor widely adopted,
well maintained packages.

### Adding Dependencies

Before adding a new dependency, search for alternatives and consider
implementing the functionality directly if it is straightforward. When
adding a dependency, review its maintenance status, community size,
security history, and license compatibility. Document the rationale
for the dependency choice.

### Updating Dependencies

Dependencies should be kept reasonably current to benefit from bug fixes
and security updates. However, frequent updates also introduce risk.
Strike a balance between staying current and ensuring stability. Major
version upgrades require more thorough testing and may require code changes.

### Removing Dependencies

Periodically review dependencies for continued necessity. Unused or
unnecessary dependencies should be removed. When removing a dependency,
ensure that any functionality it provided is either replaced or no
longer needed.

## License Compliance

### Understanding Project Licenses

The Cosmos Simulation project uses multiple licenses for different
components. Contributors must understand and respect these licenses.
The main project is licensed under an open source license detailed in
the LICENSE file. Some components may use different licenses.

### License Compatibility

When contributing code or other materials, ensure that your contribution
is compatible with the project's existing licenses. Generally, contributions
to the main codebase should be under the same license as the surrounding
code. If you wish to contribute under different terms, discuss this with
maintainers first.

### Third Party Content

Using third party content (code, images, data, etc.) requires appropriate
licensing and attribution. Never include content without proper license
rights. When including third party content, document its source and license.

### License Headers

Source files should include appropriate license headers. When creating
new files, add the standard license header. When modifying existing files,
preserve existing license headers and add your contribution under the
appropriate terms.

## Trademark Policy

### Project Name Usage

The name "Cosmos Simulation" and associated logos and trademarks are
valuable project assets. Use of project trademarks should follow this
policy to protect the project's brand and reputation.

### Permitted Use

The following uses of project trademarks are generally permitted: referring
to the project or its components, describing compatibility or integration
with the project, and discussing the project in news, commentary, or
educational contexts.

### Prohibited Use

The following uses of project trademarks are prohibited: using the project
name or logo in ways that could imply endorsement or affiliation without
permission, using the project name in domain names or social media accounts,
and using the project name in a manner that could confuse people about
the source of software or services.

### Attribution

When using project trademarks, provide clear attribution to the project.
This helps maintain trademark rights and ensures users understand they
are dealing with project related activities.

## Privacy Considerations

### User Privacy

The Cosmos Simulation project respects user privacy. The project does
not collect personal information from users without their knowledge and
consent. Any data collection that does occur should be clearly disclosed
and optional where possible.

### Data Minimization

Collect only the data that is necessary for the project's functioning.
Do not collect or store personal information unless essential. When data
must be collected, minimize the amount and duration of storage.

### Third Party Privacy

When using third party services, consider their privacy implications.
Ensure that users are informed about any data shared with third parties.
Prefer services with strong privacy practices.

### Privacy in Contributions

When making contributions, consider privacy implications for users.
Avoid introducing features that collect unnecessary personal data.
When contributions do involve data collection, document the collection
purpose, scope, and retention practices.

## AI and Machine Learning Guidelines

### AI in the Project

The Cosmos Simulation project may incorporate AI or machine learning
components for purposes such as data analysis, optimization, or user
experience improvement. All such components must follow these guidelines.

### Transparency

When the project uses AI or ML, this should be clearly disclosed to
users. Users should understand when they are interacting with AI systems
or when AI is processing their data.

### Ethical Considerations

AI components should be designed and deployed ethically. This includes
avoiding biased training data that could lead to discriminatory outcomes,
providing appropriate human oversight for AI decisions that affect users,
and considering the societal implications of AI deployment.

### AI Contribution Guidelines

Contributions that add AI or ML components should include documentation
of the approach, training data sources, evaluation methodology, and
known limitations. Such contributions should be reviewed with particular
care for ethical implications.

## Community Metrics

### Tracking Community Health

The project maintains various metrics to track community health and
growth. These metrics help inform project decisions and identify areas
for improvement. Metrics tracked include contribution frequency,
contributor diversity, issue resolution time, and community engagement.

### Metric Usage

Community metrics are used to guide project decisions, identify trends,
and recognize contributor efforts. Metrics should be interpreted in
context and should not be used as the sole basis for decisions about
individuals or contributions.

### Metric Transparency

Community metrics are generally available to the community. This
transparency helps contributors understand the project's state and
identify opportunities for contribution.

### Privacy in Metrics

When collecting metrics, respect contributor and user privacy.
Aggregate and anonymize data where possible. Do not collect metrics
that could be used to track individual contributors without their
consent.

## Recognition Programs

### Acknowledging Contributions

The Cosmos Simulation project values and recognizes the contributions
of its community members. Recognition programs help acknowledge the
hard work and dedication of contributors.

### Types of Recognition

The project offers several forms of recognition: public acknowledgment
in release notes and communications, contributor listings in project
documentation, special roles or titles for significant contributors,
and occasional awards or honors for exceptional contributions.

### Recognition Criteria

Recognition is based on the quality, impact, and consistency of
contributions. Recognition decisions consider both technical contributions
and community contributions such as mentoring, documentation, and support.

### Nomination Process

Contributors can nominate themselves or others for recognition.
Nominations should describe the contributions being recognized and
their impact on the project. Recognition decisions are made by project
leads based on community input.

## Mentorship Programs

### Learning Opportunities

The Cosmos Simulation project is committed to helping new contributors
learn and grow. Mentorship programs connect experienced contributors
with newcomers to facilitate knowledge transfer and skill development.

### Becoming a Mentee

New contributors interested in mentorship can indicate their interest
through our community channels. Mentees should be proactive in their
learning, ask questions, and be respectful of mentors' time. Setting
clear goals and expectations helps make mentorship productive.

### Becoming a Mentor

Experienced contributors are encouraged to become mentors. Mentors
should be patient, supportive, and knowledgeable. They should help
mentees find appropriate tasks, review their work constructively, and
support their growth as contributors.

### Mentorship Activities

Mentorship activities may include code reviews with explanations,
pair programming sessions, guidance on project processes and culture,
and assistance with navigating technical challenges. Mentorship should
focus on building the mentee's skills and confidence.

## Working Groups

### Purpose of Working Groups

Working groups are temporary teams formed to address specific projects
or challenges that benefit from focused collaboration. Working groups
allow contributors to work intensively on significant efforts without
being distracted by regular project activities.

### Forming Working Groups

Working groups can be proposed by any contributor. Proposals should
include the purpose and scope of the group, expected duration, and
proposed participants. Working groups require approval from project
leads.

### Working Group Operation

Working groups should have clear goals and timelines. They should
communicate regularly with the broader community through updates or
presentations. When the working group's goal is complete or the group
is no longer needed, it should be formally closed.

### Participation in Working Groups

Working groups are open to any contributor who wishes to participate.
Participation should align with the group's needs and the contributor's
interests and skills. Working group members should commit to active
participation for the group's duration.

## Roadmap Participation

### Understanding the Roadmap

The project maintains a roadmap that outlines planned features,
improvements, and priorities. The roadmap helps contributors understand
the project's direction and identify opportunities for contribution.

### Roadmap Input

The community is encouraged to provide input on the roadmap. This
includes proposing new ideas, commenting on existing plans, and
prioritizing features based on community needs. Community input is
valuable and considered seriously in roadmap decisions.

### Contributing to Roadmap Items

When roadmap items are selected for development, community members
are welcome to contribute. Contributors can claim roadmap items they
wish to work on, coordinate with others working on related items,
and provide feedback on implementation approaches.

### Roadmap Updates

The roadmap is updated regularly to reflect completed work, changing
priorities, and new opportunities. Major roadmap changes are announced
to the community with context and rationale.

## Feature Requests

### Requesting Features

Feature requests are welcome and valuable. Before submitting a request,
search for existing similar requests and add your support if found.
Describe the feature clearly, explaining what it would do and why it
would be valuable.

### Feature Request Evaluation

Feature requests are evaluated based on alignment with project goals,
technical feasibility, resource requirements, and community demand.
Not all requested features will be implemented, but all requests are
considered.

### Contributing Requested Features

If a feature request is approved for implementation, community members
can contribute it. Contributors should coordinate with others working
on similar features and follow project development practices.

### Deprecation and Removal

Sometimes features are deprecated or removed. When this happens,
affected users will be notified in advance. Documentation will explain
the deprecation timeline and any migration paths.

## Beta Testing

### Beta Program

The project may offer beta versions of upcoming releases for testing.
Beta testing helps identify issues before general release and allows
interested users to try new features early.

### Becoming a Beta Tester

Beta testers are welcome from the community. Testers should be willing
to provide feedback on new features, report bugs and issues, and
understand that beta software may be unstable.

### Beta Tester Responsibilities

Beta testers are expected to test actively and provide constructive
feedback. This includes testing on various systems and configurations,
documenting issues clearly and completely, and providing feedback on
usability and functionality.

### Beta Feedback Process

Beta feedback should be submitted through designated channels.
Feedback should be specific and actionable. Maintainers review beta
feedback and use it to improve releases before general availability.

## User Feedback

### Collecting Feedback

User feedback helps the project improve and better serve its audience.
Feedback can be collected through surveys, issue reports, discussions,
or direct communication. All feedback is valuable and considered.

### Types of Feedback

The project welcomes various types of feedback: bug reports, feature
suggestions, usability concerns, documentation improvements, and
general comments or questions. Each type of feedback helps improve
the project.

### Providing Feedback

When providing feedback, be specific and constructive. For bug reports,
include steps to reproduce, expected behavior, and environment details.
For feature suggestions, explain the use case and potential benefits.
Constructive feedback is more likely to result in positive changes.

### Feedback Response

The project endeavors to acknowledge and respond to feedback in a
timely manner. Not all feedback will result in changes, but all
feedback is read and considered. When decisions are made based on
feedback, the rationale may be shared.

## Crisis Management

### Crisis Types

Crises affecting the project may include security vulnerabilities,
significant bugs, loss of key contributors, or external events.
Crisis management procedures help the project respond effectively.

### Crisis Response

In a crisis, the project will respond according to its nature.
Security issues may require rapid patching and disclosure. Significant bugs may require emergency releases. Communication with the community is essential during crises.

### Communication During Crises

During a crisis, communication should be timely, accurate, and
appropriate to the situation. The project will provide updates as
information becomes available. Community members should monitor
official channels for crisis related communications.

### Recovery and Learning

After a crisis is resolved, the project will review what happened
and what could be improved. Lessons learned are incorporated into
project practices to prevent or mitigate future crises.

## Sustainability Practices

### Long Term Sustainability

The Cosmos Simulation project aims for long term sustainability.
This includes financial sustainability, contributor sustainability,
and technical sustainability. All contributors should consider
sustainability implications of their work.

### Contributor Sustainability

Contributing should be sustainable for all participants. Contributors
should balance project work with other life commitments. Burnout is
a real concern, and the project encourages healthy work habits.

### Technical Sustainability

Technical decisions should consider long term maintenance. This
includes choosing sustainable technologies, maintaining code quality,
and avoiding unnecessary complexity. Technical debt should be managed
proactively.

### Community Sustainability

A healthy community is essential for project sustainability. The
project values inclusivity, welcomes new contributors, and maintains
processes that support community growth and vitality.

## Comprehensive Behavioral Guidelines

### What You SHOULD Do

The following behaviors are   encouraged and expected   from all community
members. Following these guidelines helps maintain a positive, productive,
and welcoming environment for everyone:

  Communication Best Practices:  

* You SHOULD greet new members and help them feel welcome in our community
* You SHOULD use clear, respectful language that all contributors can understand
* You SHOULD provide constructive feedback that helps others improve their work
* You SHOULD acknowledge questions even if you cannot answer them fully
* You SHOULD explain technical concepts patiently when helping newer contributors
* You SHOULD verify information before sharing it as fact, especially scientific data
* You SHOULD cite sources when providing astronomical or scientific information
* You SHOULD ask clarifying questions when you don't understand something
* You SHOULD use inclusive language that welcomes contributors of all backgrounds

  Collaboration Best Practices:  

* You SHOULD review others' pull requests with helpful, specific comments
* You SHOULD test contributions before approving them in code review
* You SHOULD document your code thoroughly so others can understand it
* You SHOULD write tests for new features to ensure long term reliability
* You SHOULD update documentation when you make changes to the codebase
* You SHOULD respond to review comments within a reasonable timeframe
* You SHOULD break large changes into smaller, manageable pull requests
* You SHOULD communicate delays or issues with your assigned tasks promptly
* You SHOULD seek help when you're stuck rather than remaining blocked

  Community Participation Best Practices:  

* You SHOULD participate in community discussions and share your expertise
* You SHOULD mentor new contributors and help them learn the codebase
* You SHOULD report bugs with detailed steps to reproduce the issue
* You SHOULD suggest improvements based on your experience using the project
* You SHOULD respect the time and effort others have invested in their work
* You SHOULD celebrate the successes of other community members
* You SHOULD remain patient with contributors who are still learning
* You SHOULD acknowledge your mistakes and work to correct them
* You SHOULD vote or react to issues to show community interest and support
* You SHOULD follow through on commitments you make to the community

  Technical Best Practices:  
* You SHOULD follow the project's coding standards and style guidelines
* You SHOULD run tests and linting tools before submitting contributions
* You SHOULD use meaningful variable and function names that describe their purpose
* You SHOULD keep your contributions focused on the specific task at hand
* You SHOULD update dependencies when security vulnerabilities are discovered
* You SHOULD consider performance implications of your changes
* You SHOULD backup your work and use version control for all significant changes
* You SHOULD verify that your changes work correctly before submitting them
* You SHOULD use the project's issue tracking system for all work items
* You SHOULD respect the project's branching strategy and workflow

  Respect and Inclusion Best Practices:  
* You SHOULD treat all contributors with equal respect regardless of experience level
* You SHOULD recognize that people have different communication styles and backgrounds
* You SHOULD give others the benefit of the doubt when interpreting their words
* You SHOULD create space for quieter voices to be heard in discussions
* You SHOULD represent the project positively in all public interactions
* You SHOULD respect diverse perspectives and approaches to solving problems
* You SHOULD use people's preferred names and pronouns
* You SHOULD accommodate different time zones and work schedules when collaborating
* You SHOULD be understanding of life circumstances that may affect availability
* You SHOULD promote an environment where everyone feels safe to contribute

### What You SHOULD NOT Do

The following behaviors are   prohibited and will result in consequences  .
These actions undermine the community and will not be tolerated:

  Communication Violations:  

* You SHOULD NOT use inflammatory, offensive, or discriminatory language
* You SHOULD NOT make personal attacks or insults against other contributors
* You SHOULD NOT dismiss or belittle others' questions or contributions
* You SHOULD NOT use sarcasm or irony in ways that could be misunderstood as hostility
* You SHOULD NOT respond to questions with contempt or impatience
* You SHOULD NOT share private information about contributors without consent
* You SHOULD NOT create multiple accounts to manipulate voting or evade bans
* You SHOULD NOT flood channels with repetitive or off topic messages
* You SHOULD NOT use the project's communication channels for unrelated commercial activities
* You SHOULD NOT impersonate project maintainers or official representatives

  Collaboration Violations:  

* You SHOULD NOT submit low quality contributions without testing or documentation
* You SHOULD NOT abandon pull requests without explanation or hand off
* You SHOULD NOT ignore review feedback and refuse to make improvements
* You SHOULD NOT submit very large pull requests that make review impossible
* You SHOULD NOT make changes that break existing functionality without good reason
* You SHOULD NOT include malicious code, backdoors, or security vulnerabilities
* You SHOULD NOT commit sensitive information like API keys or passwords
* You SHOULD NOT revert others' changes without proper discussion and rationale
* You SHOULD NOT bypass code review by committing directly to protected branches
* You SHOULD NOT claim ownership of code that you did not write or create

  Technical Violations:  

* You SHOULD NOT introduce known security vulnerabilities into the codebase
* You SHOULD NOT use outdated or deprecated dependencies without justification
* You SHOULD NOT ignore performance issues that significantly impact users
* You SHOULD NOT circumvent testing requirements or submit untested code
* You SHOULD NOT introduce code that is difficult to understand or maintain
* You SHOULD NOT make changes that violate the project's license agreements
* You SHOULD NOT include copyrighted material without proper licensing
* You SHOULD NOT submit code that does not compile or run on supported platforms
* You SHOULD NOT use the project to distribute malware or harmful software
* You SHOULD NOT interfere with the project's continuous integration systems

  Community Violations:  

* You SHOULD NOT harass, threaten, or intimidate other community members
* You SHOULD NOT engage in discriminatory behavior based on protected characteristics
* You SHOULD NOT engage in any form of sexual harassment or inappropriate advances
* You SHOULD NOT retaliate against others for reporting code of conduct violations
* You SHOULD NOT create a hostile environment that drives contributors away
* You SHOULD NOT spread misinformation about the project or its contributors
* You SHOULD NOT manipulate or falsify contribution statistics or metrics
* You SHOULD NOT exploit the project for personal gain without authorization
* You SHOULD NOT disrupt community events or meetings with disruptive behavior
* You SHOULD NOT encourage others to violate this code of conduct

  Respect and Inclusion Violations:  

* You SHOULD NOT use slurs, hate speech, or symbols associated with hatred
* You SHOULD NOT mock or ridicule others' accents, language skills, or backgrounds
* You SHOULD NOT assume someone's identity, experience level, or expertise
* You SHOULD NOT gatekeep or make newcomers feel unwelcome in any way
* You SHOULD NOT dismiss contributions based on the contributor's identity
* You SHOULD NOT create or share content that is pornographic, violent, or disturbing
* You SHOULD NOT discuss controversial political or religious topics in project spaces
* You SHOULD NOT minimize or deny the experiences of marginalized contributors
* You SHOULD NOT exclude others from participation based on geographic location
* You SHOULD NOT make assumptions about someone's abilities or circumstances

## Severity Levels and Consequences

The Cosmos Simulation project maintains a comprehensive enforcement system
with ten distinct severity levels. Each level corresponds to specific types
of violations and corresponding consequences. The severity of consequences
increases with the severity and frequency of violations:

### Severity Level 1: Minor Verbal Correction

  Examples of Violations:  
* Using informal or casual language that is slightly unprofessional
* Failing to follow communication format guidelines occasionally
* Making minor formatting errors in issues or pull requests
* Submitting code with minor style inconsistencies
* Missing documentation for private or internal functions

  Community Impact:   Negligible disruption to community operations with
no harm to individuals or the project.

  Consequence:   A private, informal reminder from a community member or
maintainer explaining the issue. No formal record is created. The individual
should correct their behavior going forward.

  Expected Resolution Time:   Immediate correction expected. No follow up
required unless the behavior recurs.

### Severity Level 2: Formal Written Warning

  Examples of Violations:  
* Repeated minor violations after multiple informal reminders
* Using dismissive language when responding to new contributors
* Submitting code with significant style issues that require extensive review
* Failing to test contributions before submitting them
* Creating duplicate issues without searching first

  Community Impact:   Minor disruption to community efficiency and
potential discouragement of new contributors.

  Consequence:   A formal written warning from a maintainer documenting
the violation, the expected improvement, and a timeline for compliance.
This warning is kept in project records for reference.

  Expected Resolution Time:   Individual should demonstrate improvement
within 7 days of receiving the warning.

### Severity Level 3: Temporary Discussion Ban

  Examples of Violations:  
* Continued minor violations after formal written warning
* Making unproductive or repetitive comments in discussions
* Failing to respond to multiple review requests within two weeks
* Discussing topics unrelated to the project in project channels
* Using project channels to complain about other open source projects

  Community Impact:   Reduced efficiency in community discussions and
potential distraction from project work.

  Consequence:   Temporary ban from participating in discussion channels
for 3 days. All project interactions must be through pull request reviews
and issue comments only. Access to real time chat is suspended.

  Expected Resolution Time:   Ban is lifted after 3 days. Individual must
acknowledge the reason for the ban and commit to improved behavior.

### Severity Level 4: Pull Request Moratorium

  Examples of Violations:  
* Submitting multiple low quality pull requests without improvement
* Ignoring feedback on multiple consecutive pull requests
* Creating very large pull requests that cannot be effectively reviewed
* Making changes that break continuous integration repeatedly
* Submitting code with security issues discovered after merging

  Community Impact:   Increased burden on code reviewers and potential
risk to project stability.

  Consequence:   Temporary prohibition from submitting new pull requests
for 7 days. Individual may still review others' code, comment on issues,
and participate in discussions. Existing open pull requests remain
subject to review.

  Expected Resolution Time:   Moratorium lifted after 7 days. Individual
should demonstrate understanding of quality requirements before resuming
pull request submissions.

### Severity Level 5: Restricted Participation

  Examples of Violations:  
* Making dismissive or condescending comments toward multiple contributors
* Consistently failing to follow communication guidelines after warnings
* Engaging in unproductive arguments in project spaces
* Submitting contributions with insufficient testing multiple times
* Missing deadlines for assigned issues without communication

  Community Impact:   Negative effect on community atmosphere and
discouragement of other contributors.

  Consequence:   Restricted participation for 14 days. Individual may
only read project discussions and documentation. All contributions must
be submitted through a mentor or sponsor who reviews them beforehand.
No direct commenting or issue creation allowed.

  Expected Resolution Time:   After 14 days, individual may apply for
restricted lifting by submitting a written plan for improved participation.

### Severity Level 6: Temporary Community Ban

  Examples of Violations:  
* Using insulting or derogatory language toward community members
* Publicly embarrassing or shaming contributors for their work
* Making personal attacks during code review discussions
* Refusing to follow maintainer guidance on multiple occasions
* Submitting code with intentional simplifications or errors

  Community Impact:   Significant harm to community atmosphere and
individual wellbeing. Creates hostile environment.

  Consequence:   Temporary ban from all community participation for
30 days. Individual is completely suspended from all project spaces,
including forums, chat, issue tracking, and pull requests. This ban
is publicly visible in community records.

  Expected Resolution Time:   After 30 days, individual may request
reinstatement by providing a written acknowledgment of violations and
a detailed plan for changed behavior. Reinstatement is not guaranteed.

### Severity Level 7: Extended Community Ban

  Examples of Violations:  
* Harassing specific community members through project channels
* Making discriminatory remarks based on protected characteristics
* Continuing violations after receiving a temporary ban
* Publishing private communications without consent
* Engaging in sustained campaign of negativity toward project or contributors

  Community Impact:   Serious harm to community wellbeing and potential
departure of targeted individuals from the community.

  Consequence:   Extended ban from all community participation for 90
days. Individual is completely suspended from all project access. All
existing contributions are subject to review. A formal review will be
conducted before any reinstatement consideration.

  Expected Resolution Time:   After 90 days, individual may submit a
formal reinstatement request. Reinstatement requires unanimous approval
from project leads and demonstrated significant personal change.

### Severity Level 8: Permanent Account Suspension

  Examples of Violations:  
* Sustained harassment of one or more community members
* Making credible threats against contributors or the project
* Introducing malicious code or security exploits intentionally
* Identity fraud or impersonation of project members
* Systematic efforts to undermine project success or reputation

  Community Impact:   Severe harm to individual contributors and
potential damage to project reputation and security.

  Consequence:   Permanent suspension of all project accounts and
access. Individual is permanently banned from all project spaces,
contributions, and community activities. All existing contributions
may be removed or attributed to anonymous sources. This suspension
is permanent and non appealable.

  Expected Resolution Time:   No reinstatement possible. Individual
is permanently excluded from community participation.

### Severity Level 9: Legal Referral

  Examples of Violations:  
* Copyright infringement or license violations of significant scope
* Defamation of project maintainers or contributors
* Fraudulent activity related to project donations or funding
* Unauthorized use of project trademarks for commercial exploitation
* Computer crime including unauthorized access or disruption of systems

  Community Impact:   Legal and financial risk to the project and
its maintainers. Potential harm to community members' reputations
and livelihoods.

  Consequence:   Immediate permanent ban from all project access.
All relevant information is preserved for potential legal action.
Referral to appropriate legal authorities and law enforcement.
Communication with legal counsel for potential civil action.

  Expected Resolution Time:   Legal process follows its own timeline.
Individual is permanently excluded from community participation and
subject to legal consequences.

### Severity Level 10: Emergency Project Protection

  Examples of Violations:  

- Major security breaches or data leaks involving project secrets
- Large-scale disruptions to project infrastructure or services
- Widespread misuse of project resources for illegal purposes
- Extensive copyright infringement or license violations affecting many contributors
- Mass impersonation of project members for fraudulent activities
- Active security attack or data breach targeting the project
- Distributed denial of service or infrastructure attacks
- Social engineering attacks against project maintainers
- Introduction of malware affecting project users
- Critical infrastructure sabotage or compromise
- Imminent threat to safety of community members

  Community Impact:   Critical threat to project security, stability,
and community member safety. Potential widespread harm to users.

  Consequence:   Immediate emergency response. All access revoked
immediately. Coordination with hosting providers, security teams,
and law enforcement. Full incident response procedures activated.
All available remedies pursued including civil and criminal action.
Individual is permanently banned and reported to GitHub Security Services, Legal services & appropriate authorities.

  Expected Resolution Time:   Emergency response is immediate. Legal
and security processes follow their own timelines. Full exclusion
from project and all related services permanently.

## Escalation and Deescalation Guidelines

### Escalation Path

Violations should be escalated through the following path:

1.   Initial Detection  : Any community member or maintainer may identify
   a potential violation and report it through designated channels.

2.   Initial Assessment  : A designated coordinator reviews the report
   to determine if it constitutes a violation and estimates severity level.

3.   Investigation  : For severity levels 3 and above, an investigation
   is conducted including gathering evidence, interviewing witnesses,
   and reviewing records.

4.   Determination  : After investigation, a determination is made about
   the violation and appropriate consequence.

5.   Notification  : The individual is notified of the determination
   and consequence with full explanation and evidence.

6.   Appeal Process  : For severity levels 5 and above, the individual
   may appeal the decision through the formal appeal process.

### deescalation Considerations

In some cases, deescalation may be appropriate:

* First time violations of low severity may warrant lesser consequences
* Violations stemming from misunderstanding may be resolved through education
* Personal circumstances affecting behavior may be considered
* Demonstrated remorse and commitment to change may reduce consequences
* Genuine efforts at repair and reconciliation may influence decisions

deescalation does not apply to severe violations or repeat offenders.

### Appeal Process

For violations of severity level 5 and above, individuals may appeal:

1.   Written Appeal  : Submit a formal written appeal within 14 days of
   the decision, explaining grounds for appeal.

2.   Review Committee  : An appeal review committee is assembled,
   consisting of project leads not involved in the original decision.

3.   Review Process  : Committee reviews all evidence and hears from
   all parties before rendering a decision.

4.   Outcome  : Committee may uphold, reduce, or increase the original
   consequence. This decision is final for severity levels 5 7.

5.   Further Appeal  : For severity levels 8 10, appeals may be
   considered by external review at the project leads' discretion.

## Reporting Violations

All violations should be reported to ensure community safety:

  Report Email  : conduct@cosmos simulation.example.com

  Emergency Reports  : For urgent security concerns or threats to
safety, contact project leads directly at security@cosmos simulation.example.com

  Reporting Principles  :
- Reports should be made in good faith
- Retaliation against reporters is itself a violation
- All reports are treated confidentially
- Reports are reviewed by trained coordinators
- False reports may result in consequences for the reporter

## Enforcement Team

The code of conduct is enforced by trained coordinators:

  Level 1 2  : Community members and any maintainer
  Level 3 4  : Senior maintainers and coordinators
  Level 5 7  : Project leads with review committee
  Level 8 10  : Project leads with external consultation

All enforcement decisions are documented and tracked for consistency.

