## Glossary

### Normal Glossary

This glossary provides concise definitions of key terms used throughout this document and the Cosmos Simulation project:

-   Branch  : A parallel version of the repository that allows independent development work
-   Bug  : An error or flaw in software that produces unexpected results
-   Code Review  : The process of examining code changes before they are merged
-   Commit  : A saved change to the repository with a unique identifier
-   Contributor  : Anyone who submits code, documentation, or other work to the project
-   Documentation  : Written materials that explain how to use or understand the project
-   Fork  : A personal copy of another user's repository
-   Issue  : A tracking item for bugs, features, or tasks
-   Maintainer  : A contributor with additional responsibilities for project management
-   Merge  : Combining changes from different branches
-   Open Source  : Software with source code that anyone can view and modify
-   Pull Request  : A proposal to submit changes to the repository
-   Repository  : A storage location for project files and history
-   Reviewer  : A contributor who examines and comments on pull requests
-   Technical Debt  : The future cost of taking shortcuts in development
-   Testing  : Verifying that code works correctly
-   Version Control  : A system that records changes to files over time

#### Extended Glossary (A-Z)

  ##### A  
-   API (Application Programming Interface)  : A set of rules and protocols that allows different software applications to communicate with each other. In the Cosmos Simulation project, APIs define how the physics engine, time system, and renderer interact.
-   Astronomical Unit (AU)  : A unit of measurement equal to the average distance between Earth and the Sun, approximately 150 million kilometers. Used extensively in the project for representing astronomical distances.
-   Atomic Commit  : A commit that contains only one logical change. Atomic commits make it easier to understand history, revert changes, and isolate bugs.

  ##### B  
-   Backport  : Porting a bug fix or feature from a newer version of software to an older version. Ensures that stable releases receive important fixes without requiring users to upgrade.
-   Branch Protection  : Rules that prevent direct commits to certain branches and require pull request reviews before merging. Protects the main branch from accidental or changes.
-   Bug Report  : A detailed description of a software error, typically including steps to reproduce, expected behavior, and actual behavior. Good bug reports help developers identify and fix issues quickly.

  ##### C  
-   CI/CD (Continuous Integration/Continuous Deployment)  : Automated processes that build, test, and deploy code changes. The Cosmos Simulation project uses CI/CD to ensure code quality and automate releases.
-   Code of Conduct  : A set of guidelines that establish expectations for participant behavior in a community. This document serves as the code of conduct for the Cosmos Simulation project.
-   Code Review  : The practice of having other developers examine code changes before they are merged. Code review helps maintain code quality, share knowledge, and catch bugs early.
-   Commit Message  : A description accompanying a commit that explains what changed and why. Good commit messages make it easier to understand project history and troubleshoot issues.
-   Continuous Integration (CI)  : The practice of frequently merging code changes into a shared repository, with automated builds and tests run on each integration. Catches integration problems early.

  ##### D  
-   Dependency  : An external software package or library that the project relies on. Managing dependencies is crucial for security and stability.
-   Deprecation  : Marking a feature or API as obsolete with a plan to remove it in a future version. Gives users time to adapt before the feature is removed.
-   Documentation  : All written materials that help users and developers understand the project, including README files, API documentation, tutorials, and code comments.
-   DSA (Developer Signing Authority)  : Permission granted to contributors to sign commits on behalf of the project, verifying the commit's origin.

  ##### E  
-   End-to-End Testing  : Testing that verifies the complete functionality of an application from the user's perspective. In Cosmos Simulation, this includes testing the complete simulation experience.
-   Epic  : A large body of work that can be broken down into smaller tasks. Epics typically span multiple sprints or releases.

  ##### F  
-   Feature Branch  : A branch created for developing a new feature or improvement. Feature branches are merged into the main branch once the feature is complete and reviewed.
-   Feature Request  : A proposal for a new feature or improvement to the project. Helps the community understand user needs and prioritize development.

  ##### G  
-   Git  : A distributed version control system used for tracking changes in source code during software development. The Cosmos Simulation project uses Git for version control.
-   GitHub  : A web-based hosting service for Git repositories. Provides additional features like issue tracking, pull requests, and code review tools.
-   Glossary  : An alphabetical list of terms with definitions, helping readers understand specialized vocabulary used in a document or field.
-   GUI (Graphical User Interface)  : A visual interface that allows users to interact with software through graphical elements like buttons, menus, and visual representations. The Cosmos Simulation provides a 3D GUI for exploring the solar system.

  ##### H  
-   Hackathon  : An event where developers collaborate intensively on software projects. The Cosmos Simulation project may participate in or host hackathons.
-   HTTP (Hypertext Transfer Protocol)  : The protocol used for transferring data over the web. The project's API endpoints use HTTP for communication.

  ##### I  
-   Integration Testing  : Testing that verifies multiple components work together correctly. In Cosmos Simulation, this tests interactions between the physics engine, time system, and renderer.
-   Issue Tracker  : A tool for managing and tracking bugs, features, and tasks. The Cosmos Simulation project uses GitHub Issues for issue tracking.

  ##### J  
-   J2000  : The Julian date epoch starting at noon Universal Time on January 1, 2000. Used in astronomy as a reference point for calculations. The Cosmos Simulation project uses J2000 as its time reference.
-   Jupyter Notebook  : An interactive computing environment that supports live code, equations, visualizations, and narrative text. Useful for exploratory analysis and prototyping.
-   JSON (JavaScript Object Notation)  : A lightweight data-interchange format. Used for storing and exchanging structured data in the project.
-   JWT (JSON Web Token)  : A compact URL-safe means of representing claims to be transferred between two parties. Used for authentication and authorization in the project.

  ##### K  
-   Kepler's Laws  : Three scientific laws describing planetary motion. The physics engine uses Kepler's laws to calculate accurate orbital positions.
-   Kanban Board  : A visual tool used to manage workflow visually. Shows tasks in columns representing stages of completion.
-   Keyframe Animation  : Animating a sequence of frames to create smooth movement. Used in the Cosmos Simulation project for animating celestial bodies.
-   Keyframes  : Specific points in animation where properties like position, rotation, and scale are defined.

  ##### L  
-   LGTM  : "Looks Good To Me" - a common shorthand in code reviews indicating approval of a change.
-   License  : A legal document that defines how software can be used, modified, and distributed. The Cosmos Simulation project uses open source licenses.

  ##### M  
-   Main Branch  : The primary branch containing production-ready code. In Git workflows, the main branch typically represents the current release of the software.
-   Maintainer  : A contributor with elevated permissions and responsibilities for the project, including reviewing pull requests, managing issues, and making release decisions.
-   Merge Conflict  : A situation where Git cannot automatically combine changes from different branches because the same lines were modified differently.
-   Milestone  : A target date or goal for completing a set of issues or features. Helps track progress toward project objectives.

  ##### N  
-   Node.js  : A JavaScript runtime environment used for server-side development. The Cosmos Simulation project uses Node.js for development tools and build processes.

  ##### O  
-   Open Source  : Software with source code that is freely available for anyone to view, use, modify, and distribute. The Cosmos Simulation project is open source.
-   Orbital Mechanics  : The study of the motion of objects in space under the influence of gravitational forces. The physics engine implements accurate orbital mechanics.

  ##### P  
-   Pair Programming  : A development practice where two programmers work together at one computer, with one writing code and the other reviewing each line.
-   Patch  : A small update that fixes bugs or security vulnerabilities without adding new features.
-   POV (Point of View)  : In 3D rendering, the camera position and orientation from which a scene is viewed. Cosmos Simulation allows users to view the solar system from different POVs.
-   PR (Pull Request)  : A proposal to submit changes to a repository. Enables code review and discussion before changes are merged.
-   Protocol  : A set of rules governing communication between systems. The project uses various protocols for data exchange.

  ##### Q  
-   QA (Quality Assurance)  : Activities and processes designed to ensure software quality. Includes testing, code review, and other quality-focused practices.

  ##### R  
-   Rebase  : A Git operation that moves or combines commits from one branch onto another. Can create a cleaner commit history but requires careful handling.
-   Refactoring  : Restructuring existing code without changing its external behavior. Improves code readability, maintainability, or performance.
-   Regression  : A bug that causes previously working functionality to stop working. Regression testing helps catch these issues.
-   Release  : A version of the software made available to users. Includes bug fixes, new features, and improvements.
-   Repository  : A storage location for project files, including complete history of changes. Often called a "repo."

  ##### S  
-   Semantic Versioning (SemVer)  : A versioning scheme that communicates the nature of changes in each release (major.minor.patch).
-   Sprint  : A fixed time period during which specific work must be completed. Common in agile development methodologies.
-   Style Guide  : A set of conventions for writing code in a particular language or project. Ensures consistency across the codebase.

  ##### T  
-   Tag  : A Git reference that marks a specific commit, often used to mark releases.
-   Technical Debt  : The accumulated cost of choosing quick solutions over better approaches that would take longer to implement.
-   Testing Framework  : A tool or library that assists in writing and running tests. The project uses appropriate testing frameworks for each component.
-   Three.js  : A JavaScript 3D library used for rendering the solar system simulation. WebGLRenderer is built on Three.js.
-   Trunk-Based Development  : A version control strategy where developers merge small changes directly into the main branch frequently.

  ##### U  
-   Unit Testing  : Testing individual functions or components in isolation. Catches bugs early and helps ensure code correctness.
-   Upstream/Downstream  : Terms describing the relationship between repositories. Upstream is the original repository; downstream is a fork or derivative.

  ##### V  
-   Version Control  : A system that records changes to files over time, allowing recall of specific versions, comparison of changes, and merging of divergent changes.

  ##### W
-   WebAssembly (WASM)  : A binary instruction format for a stack-based virtual machine. WASM enables high-performance execution of compiled languages in modern web browsers.
-   WebSocket  : A protocol providing full-duplex communication channels over a single TCP connection. Used for real-time updates in the Cosmos Simulation project.
-   Whiteboard  : A collaborative drawing tool used for brainstorming ideas, planning, and documenting discussions.
-   WebGL  : A JavaScript API for rendering interactive 2D and 3D graphics in web browsers. Used by the Cosmos Simulation renderer.

  ##### X
-   XML (eXtensible Markup Language)  : A markup language similar to HTML but more flexible and extensible. Used for configuration files and data interchange.
-   XPath  : A query language for navigating and selecting nodes in XML documents. Used for parsing and manipulating data in the project.

  ##### Y
-   YAML (YAML Ain't Markup Language)  : A human-readable data serialization standard. Used for configuration files and data interchange in the project.
-   YAML Schema  : A specification defining the structure and constraints of YAML files. Ensures consistent formatting and validation.
-   YAML Validator  : A tool that checks YAML files against a schema to ensure compliance with defined standards.

  ##### Z
-   Zero Trust Architecture  : A cybersecurity model that assumes every entity inside and outside the network could potentially pose a threat. Applies strict access controls regardless of identity.
-   Zen of Python  : A collection of guiding principles for writing clear and readable Python code. Influences the design philosophy behind the Cosmos Simulation project.
